  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- First international efforts to address financial crime\n- Limited regulatory frameworks\n\n2. 1980s-1990s Developments\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- International cooperation increased\n- More comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Enhanced reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n3. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Stronger emphasis on combating terrorist financing\n- Expanded financial surveillance mechanisms\n- Increased international information sharing\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Landscape\n- More stringent Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency and blockchain transaction regulations\n- Corporate transparency laws\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Advanced technology-driven compliance\n- Risk-based approach to AML\n- Global beneficial ownership registries\n- Expanded regulations covering emerging financial technologies\n\nThese evolving legislative efforts aim to create more robust, comprehensive frameworks for detecting and preventing financial crimes.",
